    {
      "id": "-sXbb6l_0Omj0gVqHznS-",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1198.5677486311233,
      "y": 594.5510599721637,
      "width": 462.9991185947065,
      "height": 300,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ak",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 663682127,
      "version": 1217,
      "versionNonce": 1483831119,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776502308926,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "    1. We train a supervised model to learn to predict the\nparasitic params from the s params. Then we take the model\nweight matrices and fit that as W_e_1. In this case, we will\nget a pre-trained first encoder part of the whole AE type\nmodel. This is great but this is probably not the way AEs are\nusually trained.\n    2. We define the initial set of parasitic params to be within\ncertain ranges. This would act as a guardrail for each of the\nparasitic params' values and help the model converge to the\nideal values. In this case, the W_e_1 and W_e_2 matrices\nwould be formed from scratch and not need any pre-training.\n    3. We define a part of the overall loss to be the\ncomparative loss between the model's representation of the\nparasitic param. space and the actual ground truth parasitic\nparams. This way we could bake the guardrails right into\noptimization.",
      "fontSize": 15,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "    1. We train a supervised model to learn to predict the parasitic params from the s params. Then we take the model weight matrices and fit that as W_e_1. In this case, we will get a pre-trained first encoder part of the whole AE type model. This is great but this is probably not the way AEs are usually trained.\n    2. We define the initial set of parasitic params to be within certain ranges. This would act as a guardrail for each of the parasitic params' values and help the model converge to the ideal values. In this case, the W_e_1 and W_e_2 matrices would be formed from scratch and not need any pre-training.\n    3. We define a part of the overall loss to be the comparative loss between the model's representation of the parasitic param. space and the actual ground truth parasitic params. This way we could bake the guardrails right into optimization.",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "l0P7NBXtppIMc3CqmAp0N",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1852.6896302974196,
      "y": 280.5457065492775,
      "width": 270.10626993557753,
      "height": 168.75,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "al",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 674601729,
      "version": 282,
      "versionNonce": 928735356,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1776502499416,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Dataset:\n\nEarlier, the number of rows in the\ndataset was the number of\nfrequency points for which we\nobtained the S11 parameter. This\ntime, our rows in the dataset will be\nthe number of runs of ADS, i.e.\n20000. ",
      "fontSize": 15,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Dataset:\n\nEarlier, the number of rows in the dataset was the number of frequency points for which we obtained the S11 parameter. This time, our rows in the dataset will be the number of runs of ADS, i.e. 20000. ",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
